# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
1-> We can use window sliding and keep all the values in map that can tell us min and max value in that window.
2-> If the range (i.e., max-min) is greater than limit then we need to delete element from the left of window that we can do using map in O(1).

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
1 -> keep inserting the values in map and keep increasing the size of window, until we found max-min>limit and Keep updating the size of window as answer.
2-> If max-min>limit, then we can start deleting the values from map. This can be done by getting the left indexes of window and acces the value at that index and delete it from map.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
since we are using map here, so complexity for map is O(Nlog(N));
and we are traversing the array from 0-N then it'll take O(N);

So overall, **Time complexity: O(Nlog(N))**.

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
since we are using one extra map here, so **space complexity is O(N)**.

# Code
