# Intuition
The problem asks us to find the length of the longest strictly increasing subsequence in the given array. To solve this problem efficiently, we can use dynamic programming.

# Approach
1. Create a vector dp of size nums.size(), where dp[i] will store the length of the longest increasing subsequence ending at index i.
2. Initialize a variable maxlength to store the maximum length of the subsequence.
3. Set dp[0] to 1, as the length of the subsequence ending at the first index is always 1.
4. Iterate through each element in nums using the outer loop. For each element at index i, iterate through all the previous elements using the inner loop (from 0 to i-1).
5. Check if nums[i] is greater than nums[j], indicating that we can extend the increasing subsequence.
    - If the condition is satisfied, update the currentMaxLen variable with the maximum length of the subsequence so far at index j.
6. After the inner loop, update dp[i] with currentMaxLen + 1, which represents the maximum length of the subsequence ending at index i.
Update maxlength by taking the maximum value between maxlength and dp[i].
7. After the loop, maxlength will contain the length of the longest increasing subsequence.
8. Return maxlength.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
The time complexity of this solution is O(n^2), where n is the size of the input array nums. The outer loop runs for n iterations, and the inner loop also runs for a maximum of n iterations.

- Space complexity:
The space complexity is O(n) since we are using an additional vector dp of size n to store the lengths of subsequences.

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int lengthOfLIS(vector<int>& nums) {
        //array to store max length subsequence till that place
        vector<int> dp(nums.size(),0);
        int maxlength = 0;//to store maxlength of subsequence
        dp[0] = 1;//length will be 1 at first index 
        for(int i = 0;i<nums.size();i++){
            int currentMaxLen = 0; //to store maxlength at till this index
            for(int j = 0;j<i;j++){
                // only check when the subsequence is increasing
                if(nums[i]>nums[j]){
                    if(currentMaxLen<dp[j]){
                        currentMaxLen = dp[j]; //update currentMaxLen accordingly
                    }
                }
            }
            dp[i] = currentMaxLen + 1; //set the maxLength till ith index, which will be maxlenth so far + 1
            maxlength = max(maxlength,dp[i]); //update maxlength
        }

        return maxlength;
    }
};
```

