# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
We can iterate over all possible values of x and check if there are exactly x numbers in nums that are greater than or equal to x. If we find such a value of x, we can return it as the answer. If we have checked all possible values of x and none of them satisfy the condition, we can return -1.
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
- Sort the array in descending order.
- Iterate over all possible values of x from 1 to n (the length of the array).
- For each value of x, count the number of elements in the array that are greater than or equal to x. If the count is exactly x, return x as the answer.
- If we have checked all possible values of x and none of them satisfy the condition, return -1.
# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$$O(n^2)$$
- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$$O(1)$$
# Brute force Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int specialArray(vector<int>& nums) {
        int n = nums.size();
        sort(nums.begin(),nums.end(),greater<int>());
        for(int i=1;i<=n;i++){
            int cnt=0;
            for(int j=0;j<n;j++){
                if(nums[j]>=i){
                    cnt++;
                }
            }
            if(cnt==i){
                return i;
            }
        }
        return -1;
    }
};
```
