# Optimized Approach (Using Binary Search)
# Intuition

we can optimize the time complexity of the solution from O(n^2) to O(n log n) by using binary search instead of iterating over all possible values of x.
# Approach
- Sort the array in non-increasing order.
- Set the left pointer to 1 and the right pointer to n (the length of the array).
- While the left pointer is less than or equal to the right pointer:
  - Set the mid pointer to the average of the left and right pointers.
  -  Count the number of elements in the array that are greater than or equal to mid. If the count is less than mid, set the right pointer to mid-1. If the count is greater than or equal to mid, set the left pointer to mid+1.
- If we have checked all possible values of x and none of them satisfy the condition, return -1. Otherwise, return the value of mid.


The key idea behind this algorithm is that the number of elements in the array that are greater than or equal to x is a monotonic function of x. Therefore, we can use binary search to find the smallest value of x such that there are exactly x elements in the array that are greater than or equal to x.
# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int specialArray(vector<int>& nums) {
        int n = nums.size();
        sort(nums.begin(),nums.end(),greater<int>());
        int left=1,right=n;

        while(left<=right){
            int mid=(left+right)/2;
            int cnt=0;
            for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
                if(nums[i]>=mid){
                    cnt++;
                }else{
                    break;
                }
            }
            if(cnt<mid){
                right=mid-1;
            }else{
                left=mid+1;
            }
        }

        if(right<1 || nums[right-1]<right){
            return -1;
        }
        int cal=0;
        for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
            if(nums[i]>=right){
                cal++;
            }
        }
        if(cal==right){
            return right;
        }else{
            return -1;
        }
        return right;
    }
};
```
# Time Complexity 
$$O(nlogn)$$
# Space Complexity
$$O(1)$$

